WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:07.040
Part IV of The Strange Case of Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde.

00:22.680 --> 00:24.760
Doctor Lanyon's Narrative

00:27.240 --> 00:34.760
On the ninth of January, now four days ago, I received by the evening delivery a registered

00:34.760 --> 00:40.260
envelope addressed in the hand of my colleague and old school companion Henry Jekyll.

00:41.140 --> 00:47.040
I was a good deal surprised by this, for we were by no means in the habit of correspondence.

00:47.800 --> 00:53.660
I had seen the man dine with him indeed the night before, and I could imagine nothing

00:53.660 --> 00:57.640
in our intercourse that should justify formality of registration.

00:58.580 --> 01:04.420
The contents increased my wonder, for this is how the letter ran.

01:07.000 --> 01:08.200
Tenth December

01:09.180 --> 01:15.760
Dr. Lanyon, you are one of my oldest friends, and although we may have differed at times

01:15.760 --> 01:23.280
on scientific questions, I cannot remember, at least on my side, any break in our affection.

01:24.540 --> 01:31.760
There was never a day when, if you had said to me, Jekyll, my life, my honour, my reason

01:31.760 --> 01:37.900
depend upon you, I would not have sacrificed my left hand to help you.

01:38.900 --> 01:45.920
Lanyon, my life, my honour, my reason are all at your mercy.

01:46.640 --> 01:50.200
If you fail me to-night, I am lost.

01:51.660 --> 01:57.280
You might suppose, after this preface, that I am going to ask you for something dishonourable

01:57.280 --> 01:57.900
to grant.

01:58.840 --> 02:00.540
Judge for yourself.

02:01.820 --> 02:08.260
I want you to postpone all other engagements for to-night, by even if you were summoned

02:08.260 --> 02:14.340
to the bedside of an emperor, to take a cab, unless your carriage should be actually at

02:14.340 --> 02:20.540
the door, and with this letter in your hand for consultation, to drive straight to my

02:20.540 --> 02:21.100
house.

02:21.760 --> 02:24.080
Poole, my butler, has his orders.

02:24.540 --> 02:27.840
You will find him waiting your arrival with a locksmith.

02:28.340 --> 02:35.480
The door of my cabinet is then to be forced, and you are to go in alone, to open the glazed

02:35.480 --> 02:43.620
press, letter E, on the left hand, breaking the lock if it be shut, and to draw out, with

02:43.620 --> 02:50.580
all its contents as they stand, the fourth drawer from the top, or, which is the same

02:50.580 --> 02:52.760
thing, the third from the bottom.

02:53.540 --> 03:01.380
In my extreme distress of mind, I have a morbid fear of misdirecting you, but even if I am

03:01.380 --> 03:08.600
in error, you may know the right drawer by its contents, some powders, a file, and a

03:08.600 --> 03:09.360
paper book.

03:10.080 --> 03:17.200
This drawer I beg of you to carry back with you to Cavendish Square, exactly as it stands.

03:17.200 --> 03:22.880
This is the first part of the service, now for the second.

03:23.680 --> 03:29.860
You should be back if you set out at once on the receipt of this long before midnight,

03:30.480 --> 03:35.840
but I will leave you that amount of margin, not only in the fear of one of those obstacles

03:35.840 --> 03:41.580
that can neither be prevented nor foreseen, but because an hour when your servants are

03:41.580 --> 03:46.040
in bed is to be preferred for what will then remain to do.

03:46.980 --> 03:54.300
At midnight then, I have to ask you to be alone in your consulting room, to admit with

03:54.300 --> 04:01.380
your own hand into the house a man who will present himself in my name, and to place in

04:01.380 --> 04:05.600
his hands the drawer that you will have brought with you from my cabinet.

04:06.580 --> 04:12.060
Then you will have played your part, and earned my gratitude completely.

04:13.020 --> 04:19.640
Five minutes afterwards, if you insist upon an explanation, you will have understood that

04:19.640 --> 04:26.600
these arrangements are of capital importance, and that by the neglect of one of them, fantastic

04:26.600 --> 04:33.520
as they must appear, you might have charged your conscience with my death, or the shipwreck

04:33.520 --> 04:34.580
of my reason.

04:36.560 --> 04:43.260
Confident as I am that you will not trifle with this appeal, my heart sinks, and my hand

04:43.260 --> 04:46.260
trembles at the bare thought of such a possibility.

04:47.620 --> 04:54.260
Think of me at this hour in a strange place, laboring under a blackness of distress that

04:54.260 --> 05:02.120
no fancy can exaggerate, and yet well aware that, if you will but punctually serve me,

05:02.120 --> 05:06.420
my troubles will roll away like a story that is told.

05:07.280 --> 05:13.820
Serve me, my dear Lanyon, and save your friend, Henry Jekyll.

05:15.240 --> 05:20.780
P.S. I had already sealed this up when a fresh terror struck upon my soul.

05:21.600 --> 05:27.580
It is possible that the post-office may fail me, and this letter not come into your hands

05:27.580 --> 05:28.880
until to-morrow morning.

05:29.580 --> 05:35.960
In that case, dear Lanyon, do my errand when it shall be most convenient for you in the

05:35.960 --> 05:40.700
course of the day, and once more expect my messenger at midnight.

05:41.420 --> 05:50.060
It may then already be too late, and if that night passes without event, you will know

05:50.060 --> 05:53.880
that you have seen the last of Henry Jekyll.

05:57.740 --> 06:05.080
Upon reading of this letter I made sure my colleague was insane, but till that was proved

06:05.080 --> 06:10.240
beyond the possibility of doubt, I felt bound to do as he requested.

06:11.340 --> 06:16.620
The less I understood of this farrago, the less I was in a position to judge of its importance,

06:17.260 --> 06:22.420
and an appeal so worded could not be set aside without a grave responsibility.

06:23.340 --> 06:29.740
I rose accordingly from my table, got into a hansom, and drove straight to Jekyll's house.

06:30.560 --> 06:32.960
The butler was awaiting my arrival.

06:33.400 --> 06:37.920
He had received by the same post as mine a registered letter of instruction,

06:38.480 --> 06:41.980
and had sent at once for a locksmith and a carpenter.

06:42.860 --> 06:49.140
The tradesman came while we were yet speaking, and we moved in a body to old Dr. Denman's

06:49.140 --> 06:55.180
surgical theatre, from which, as you are doubtlessly aware, Jekyll's private cabinet

06:55.180 --> 06:57.220
is most conveniently entered.

06:57.840 --> 07:04.460
The door was very strong, the lock excellent, the carpenter avowed he would have great trouble

07:04.460 --> 07:11.340
and have to do much damage if force were to be used, and the locksmith was near despair.

07:11.900 --> 07:18.760
But this last was a handy fellow, and after two hours' work the door stood open.

07:19.140 --> 07:25.800
The press marked E was unlocked, and I took out the drawer, had it filled up with straw

07:25.800 --> 07:30.660
and tied in a sheet, and returned with it to Cavendish Square.

07:31.880 --> 07:34.840
Here I proceeded to examine its contents.

07:35.400 --> 07:41.580
The powders were neatly enough made up, but not with the nicety of the dispensing chemist,

07:41.940 --> 07:45.680
so that it was plain they were of Jekyll's private manufacture,

07:45.680 --> 07:51.040
and when I opened one of the wrappers I found what seemed to me a simple

07:51.040 --> 07:53.560
crystal and salt of a white colour.

07:54.500 --> 08:01.680
The file to which I next turned my attention might have been about half full of a blood red liquor,

08:02.200 --> 08:08.040
which was highly pungent to the sense of smell, and seemed to me to contain phosphorus

08:08.040 --> 08:10.280
and some volatile ether.

08:11.580 --> 08:14.780
At the other ingredients I could make no guess.

08:15.420 --> 08:20.800
The book was an ordinary version book, and contained little but a series of dates.

08:21.900 --> 08:24.660
These covered a period of many years,

08:24.960 --> 08:30.320
but I observed that the entries ceased nearly a year ago, and quite abruptly.

08:31.500 --> 08:36.960
Here and there a brief remark was appended to a date, usually no more than a single word,

08:37.720 --> 08:42.060
double occurring perhaps six times in a total of several hundred entries,

08:42.060 --> 08:48.600
and once very early in the list, and followed by several marks of exclamation,

08:49.380 --> 08:50.840
total failure.

08:52.560 --> 08:57.720
All this, though it whetted my curiosity, told me little that was definite.

08:58.260 --> 09:05.060
Here was a file of some sort, and the record of a series of experiments that had led,

09:05.460 --> 09:11.240
like too many of Jekyll's investigations, to no end of practical usefulness.

09:12.160 --> 09:18.240
How could the presence of these articles in my house affect either the honour, the sanity,

09:18.600 --> 09:21.220
or the life of my flighty colleague?

09:22.220 --> 09:26.600
If his messenger could go to one place, why could he not go to another?

09:27.240 --> 09:33.880
And even granting such impediment, why was this gentleman to be received by me in secret?

09:35.100 --> 09:40.840
The more I reflected, the more convinced I grew that I was dealing with a case of

09:40.840 --> 09:47.980
cerebral disease, and though I dismissed my servants to bed, I loaded an old revolver

09:47.980 --> 09:52.140
that I might be found in some posture of self-defence.

09:53.780 --> 09:57.000
Twelve o'clock had scarce brung out over London,

09:57.480 --> 10:00.940
ere the knocker sounded very gently on the door.

10:01.420 --> 10:08.400
I went myself at the summons, and found a small man crouching against the pillars of the portico.

10:09.220 --> 10:12.560
"'Are you from Dr. Jekyll?' I asked.

10:13.180 --> 10:19.160
He told me yes by a constrained gesture, and when I had bidden him enter,

10:19.420 --> 10:25.520
he did not obey me without a searching backward glance into the darkness of the square.

10:26.500 --> 10:33.000
There was a policeman not far off, advancing with his bullseye open, and at the sight,

10:33.600 --> 10:37.760
I thought my visitor started, and made greater haste.

10:38.400 --> 10:44.940
These particulars struck me, I confess, disagreeably, and as I followed him into

10:44.940 --> 10:50.060
the bright light of the consulting-room, I kept my hand ready on my weapon.

10:50.800 --> 10:54.380
Here, at last, I had a chance of clearly seeing him.

10:54.780 --> 10:58.480
I had never set eyes on him before, so much was certain.

10:59.260 --> 11:01.400
He was small, as I have said.

11:01.820 --> 11:05.920
I was struck besides with the shocking expression of his face,

11:05.920 --> 11:12.760
with this remarkable combination of great muscular activity, and great apparent debility

11:12.760 --> 11:20.960
of constitution, and last but not least with the odd subjective disturbance caused by his neighborhood.

11:22.180 --> 11:28.880
This bore some resemblance to incipient rigor, and was accompanied by a marked sinking of the pulse.

11:29.700 --> 11:35.060
At the time, I set it down to some idiosyncratic personal distaste,

11:35.060 --> 11:38.480
and merely wondered at the acuteness of the symptoms.

11:39.260 --> 11:45.280
But I have since had reason to believe the cause to lie much deeper in the nature of the man,

11:45.740 --> 11:49.980
and to turn on some nobler hinge than the principle of hatred.

11:51.260 --> 11:57.280
This person, who had thus from the first moment of his entrance struck in me what I can only

11:57.280 --> 12:04.680
describe as a disgustful curiosity, was dressed in a fashion that would have made an ordinary

12:04.680 --> 12:11.520
person laughable. His clothes, that is to say, although they were of rich and sober fabric,

12:11.900 --> 12:18.220
were enormously too large for him in every measurement, the trousers hanging on his legs,

12:18.480 --> 12:24.120
and rolled up to keep them from the ground, the waist of the coat below his hunches,

12:24.560 --> 12:27.680
and the collar sprawling wide upon his shoulders.

12:28.660 --> 12:36.060
Strange to relate, this ludicrous accoutrement was far from moving me to laughter. Rather,

12:36.320 --> 12:42.760
as there was something abnormal and misbegotten in the very essence of the creature that now faced me,

12:43.220 --> 12:50.680
something seizing, surprising, and revolting, this fresh disparity seemed but to fit in with

12:50.680 --> 12:57.600
and to reinforce it, so that, to my interest in the man's nature and character, there was added

12:57.600 --> 13:06.380
curiosity as to his origin, his life, his fortune and status in the world. These observations,

13:06.880 --> 13:13.280
though they have taken so great a space to be set down in, were yet the work of a few seconds.

13:14.000 --> 13:18.700
My visitor was indeed on fire with sombre excitement.

13:19.180 --> 13:26.340
Have you got it? he cried. Have you got it? And so lively was his impatience

13:26.340 --> 13:30.940
that he even laid his hand upon my arm and sought to shake me.

13:31.900 --> 13:38.220
I put him back, conscious at his touch of a certain icy pang along my blood.

13:39.120 --> 13:45.020
Come, sir, said I. You forgot that I have not yet the pleasure of your acquaintance.

13:45.020 --> 13:53.560
Be seated, if you please. Then I showed him an example, and sat down myself in my customary seat,

13:53.980 --> 13:59.860
and with as fair an imitation of my ordinary manner to a patient as the lateness of the hour,

14:00.220 --> 14:06.780
the nature of my preoccupations, and the horror I had of my visitor, would suffer me to muster.

14:07.660 --> 14:16.160
I beg your pardon, Dr. Lanyon, he replied, civilly enough. What you say is very well founded,

14:16.760 --> 14:20.060
and my impatience has shown its heels to my politeness.

14:21.140 --> 14:28.200
I came here at the instance of your colleague, Dr. Henry Jekyll, on a piece of business of

14:28.200 --> 14:36.200
some moment, and I understood. He paused and put his hand to his throat, and I could see,

14:36.200 --> 14:42.240
in spite of his collected manner, that he was wrestling against the approaches of the hysteria.

14:43.220 --> 14:49.600
I understood a drawer, but here I took pity on my visitor's suspense,

14:49.860 --> 14:52.920
and some perhaps on my own growing curiosity.

14:53.620 --> 14:58.040
There it is, sir, said I, pointing to the drawer,

14:58.360 --> 15:02.720
where it lay on the floor behind a table, and still covered with the sheet.

15:03.540 --> 15:08.860
He sprang to it, and then paused, and laid his hand upon his heart.

15:09.680 --> 15:13.860
I could hear his teeth grate with the convulsive action of his jaws,

15:14.300 --> 15:20.660
and his face was so ghastly to see, that I grew alarmed both for his life and reason.

15:21.740 --> 15:27.500
Compose yourself, said I. He turned a dreadful smile to me,

15:27.940 --> 15:32.440
and as if with the decision of despair, plucked away the sheet.

15:32.720 --> 15:40.880
At sight of the contents, he uttered one loud sob of such immense relief, that I sat petrified,

15:41.640 --> 15:46.300
and the next moment, in a voice that was already fairly well under control,

15:46.840 --> 15:50.860
have you a graduated glass? he asked.

15:52.240 --> 15:57.300
I rose from my place with something of an effort, and gave him what he asked.

15:58.240 --> 16:04.760
He thanked me with a smiling nod, measured out a few minims of the red tincture,

16:05.140 --> 16:12.280
and added one of the powders. The mixture, which was at first a reddish hue, began,

16:12.320 --> 16:18.360
in proportion as the crystals melted, to brighten in colour, to effervesce audibly,

16:18.740 --> 16:24.880
and to throw off small fumes of vapour. Suddenly, and at the same moment,

16:24.880 --> 16:33.020
the ebullition ceased, and the compound changed to a dark purple, which faded again more slowly

16:33.020 --> 16:40.920
to a watery green. My visitor, who had watched these metamorphoses with a keen eye, smiled,

16:41.440 --> 16:47.960
set down the glass upon the table, and then turned and looked upon me with an air of scrutiny.

16:49.040 --> 16:53.920
And now, said he, to settle what remains.

16:55.380 --> 17:04.540
Will you be wise? will you be guided? will you suffer me to take this glass in my hand,

17:04.580 --> 17:07.800
and to go forth from your house without further parley?

17:08.880 --> 17:15.840
Or has the greed of curiosity too much command of you? Think before you answer,

17:15.840 --> 17:25.000
for it shall be done as you decide. As you decide, you shall be left as you were before,

17:25.380 --> 17:32.140
and neither richer nor wiser, unless the sense of service rendered to a man in mortal distress

17:32.140 --> 17:39.960
may be counted as a kind of riches of the soul. Or, if you shall so prefer to choose,

17:39.960 --> 17:47.020
a new province of knowledge, a new avenue to fame and power, shall be laid open to you,

17:47.260 --> 17:55.680
here, in this room, upon the instant, and your sight shall be blasted by a prodigy to stagger

17:55.680 --> 18:03.920
the unbelief of Satan. Sir, said I, affecting a coolness that I was far from truly possessing,

18:04.580 --> 18:11.160
You speak enigmas, and you will perhaps not wonder that I hear you with no very strong

18:11.160 --> 18:17.300
impression of belief. But I have gone too far in the way of inexplicable services

18:17.300 --> 18:20.340
to pause before I see the end.

18:21.800 --> 18:29.540
It is well, replied my visitor. Lanyon, you remember your vows.

18:29.540 --> 18:40.180
What follows is under the seal of our profession. And now, you who have so long been bound to the

18:40.180 --> 18:47.660
most narrow and material views, you who have denied the virtue of transcendental medicine,

18:48.420 --> 18:53.420
you who have derided your superiors, behold.

18:54.540 --> 19:03.380
He put the glass to his lips, and drank at one gulp. A cry followed. He reeled, staggered,

19:03.600 --> 19:10.080
clutched at the table, and held on, staring with injected eyes, gasping with open mouth.

19:10.520 --> 19:19.620
And as I looked, there came, I thought, a change. He seemed to swell. His face became suddenly black,

19:19.620 --> 19:27.580
and the feature seemed to melt and alter. And the next moment I had sprung to my feet,

19:27.940 --> 19:33.960
and leaped back against the wall, my arms raised to shield me from that prodigy.

19:34.440 --> 19:37.300
My mind submerged in terror.

19:38.260 --> 19:50.380
O God! I screamed, and O God! again and again. For there, before my eyes, pale and shaken,

19:50.860 --> 19:57.600
and half fainting, and groping before him with his hands, like a man restored from death,

19:58.480 --> 20:02.260
there stood Henry Jekyll.

20:05.160 --> 20:14.400
What he told me in the next hour, I cannot bring my mind to set on paper. I saw what I saw,

20:14.820 --> 20:23.320
I heard what I heard, and my soul sickened at it. And yet, now when that sight has faded from my

20:23.320 --> 20:32.240
eyes, I ask myself if I believe it, and I cannot answer. My life is shaken to its roots.

20:32.240 --> 20:40.360
Sleep has left me. The deadliest terror sits by me at all hours of the day and the night,

20:40.640 --> 20:49.600
and I feel that my days are numbered. And then I must die, and yet I shall die incredulous.

20:50.580 --> 20:58.040
As for the moral turpitude that man unveiled to me, even with tears of penitence, I cannot,

20:58.040 --> 21:06.380
even in memory, dwell on it without a start of horror. I will say but one thing, Utterson,

21:07.080 --> 21:13.820
and that, if you can bring your mind to credit it, will be more than enough. The creature that

21:13.820 --> 21:22.060
crept into my house that night was on Jekyll's own confession, known by the name of Hyde,

21:22.060 --> 21:28.660
and hunted for in every corner of the land as the murderer of Coru.

21:31.160 --> 21:32.600
Hastey Lanyon

21:35.840 --> 21:38.100
End of part four

